<text> FLUORESCENCE
p. 1 of 6

 
 http://www.nist.gov/public_affairs/techbeat/tb2004_0226.htm#tagging
 Fluorescent particles 15 nm are attached to particular genes in DNA.


It is a challenge to see small things and small amounts of substances.  If these can be made to glow against a dark background, they can be seen more easily. Because this approach is so promising, a whole of field of fluorescence science is flourishing today. 

 What is fluorescence?

Fluorescence is the short-lived glow produced when electrons of an atom or molecule, which have absorbed energy from a source like ultraviolet (UV) light and been excited to a higher orbital, sink back to a lower orbital, releasing the absorbed energy as light or heat.


This is a two-step process in which typically two photons are released, unless in one of the steps some of the extra energy is converted into heat. This two-step process distinguishes it from any other types of light emission. 

It can be contrasted with reflection or better, scattering, in which, after being absorbed,  a photon of the same energy is released.


 The uses of fluorescence. 

Fluorescence has many applications in lighting, mineralogy, biochemistry, medicine, and forensics. It is particularly important in biotechnology. Scientists can see structures of interest, such as the ladder of DNA; they can see where in a cell a substance is located or in which direction it is traveling.

Fluorescent chemical groups can be attached or &quot;complexed&quot; to targetted biological molecules through certain chemical reactions. These fluorescent tags can be easily detected by shining ultraviolet light on the samples. 


